history.content:
The 10% rule is not a rule as such, but just a rough general estimate. Your waitlist positions do not look good, but if you don't have other high priority classes in mind, you could choose to stick with them. Use your own judgement.

---

Also want to add that the 10% rule does not apply to some of the "let everyone in" classes in case people are unfamiliar with them. From what I understand, for CS 61A/B/C, CS 70, and CS 170, your waitlist positions generally do not matter during P1/P2. Also, for classes like CS 189, the drop rate is very high since people vastly underestimate the mathematical maturity required for the class, so you could be WL #100 in a full 189 and still get in, as long as its early enough in the semester. Correct me if I'm wrong.

Does the 10 percent rule for waitlisting (if you're waitlist number is 10 percent of the total class enrollment, you should wait, otherwise you should find another class) still apply now that the Phase 1 enrollment cap has risen to 13.5 units and many people are signing up for more classes than they plan to take? I'm a declared CS major but I'm above the 10 percent rule for classes I really want to take, so I'm not sure if I should stick with them or not.
